<br>
First Timer's Raid Guide *this is a work in progress*<br>
<br>
So you're going on your first raid. Welcome to a fun, exciting, but very different part of Everquest. A lot of things are different on a raid, and to help you adjust, we have this guide. If this is your first time going on a raid with the Sentinels, please read it thorougly and ask your group leader any questions you might have. You should also read the Raid Rules, posted in this forum.<br>
<br>
First things first<br>
Your work for the raid starts early. The first thing you should do is be on time, and be ready. If the raid starts at 7:00 (and be sure to check time zones) then be at the designated location at 7:00. Not at 7:15, not at 7:30, don't log on at 6:58 and start looking for a port. Be there and be ready. By &quot;be ready&quot; I mean have enough food/water/reagents (except peridots) etc to hold you for the night. If everyone is on time and ready, things go much smoother.<br>
<br>
The most important things you can do<br>
These are the three most important things you can do on a raid.<br>
<br>
1. Listen to the raid leaders.<br>
2. Do what you are told, when you are told.<br>
3. Do not do what you are not told.<br>
<br>
Sounds pretty simple, and it is. But most of the time, problems on a raid come from someone breaking one of these rules. If the raid leader says wait, then wait, and do so patiently. If they're not saying anything, then wait patiently til they do. Don't go wandering off or playing with the Eye of Zomm. Things like that get raids wiped out - just wait patiently and chat with your group. Raids involve a lot of hurry up and wait, and if you're prepared for this, you'll have a lot more fun. Make sure you know who the raid leaders are for this raid, and anyone else you should be listening to.<br>
<br>
Channels<br>
Generally on our raids, the raid leaders will use the /shout channel. Nobody else should be using it. Most of the time people will generally chat and kid around in /ooc. If you have a question about something the raid leader just said, ask your group leader, or if necessary ask in /ooc. Don't use /shout unless you're supposed to. It makes it easier for people to see important messages.<br>
<br>
Assisting<br>
This is a really important thing you have to learn on raids. If you've solo'd a lot, this might be new to you.<br>
<br>
The first thing you need to do is make sure that when you use the /assist command, you do not automatically start attacking. Do this by issuing the command:<br>
<br>
/assist off<br>
<br>
During the prep time, the raid leader will announce the Main Assist (MA) and Secondary Assist (SA) Make two hotkeys after they are announced. (Let's say they announce that the main assist is Fred and the secondary assist is Steve). Set up two hotkeys - one says<br>
<br>
/assist Fred<br>
<br>
the other says<br>
<br>
/assist Steve<br>
<br>
Now let me tell you why this is so important. When you have a monster under attack in a raid situation, the idea is to keep that monster hitting a single person - the main assist (MA). Fred should be the one taking all the damage. You shouldn't taunt unless you're Fred. You should be avoiding getting hit if you're not Fred. Rogues should evade, monks should feign, casters should hold nukes until the health is run down some so that the monster is always attacking Fred. Controlling agro is key to a successful raid.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, we need everyone on the same target. If a pull brings in three mobs, the enchanters will mesmerize two, and Fred will attack one. If you are not attacking the same mob that Fred is, you will break the mez, and cause a lot of disruption.<br>
<br>
So let me give you an example. Our raiders are about to attack a fearsome orc pawn in the hellish dimension of East Commons.<br>
<br>
The puller brings in the orc pawn, and feigns death near the group, but not terribly close. Unfortunately with the orc pawn came two orc centurions. If fought all at once, they would surely destroy our raiders.<br>
<br>
The MA fires an arrow at the orc pawn. The pawn and his two centurion friends come to the camp. You do nothing.<br>
<br>
The orcs are beating on whoever they see fit. Fred is attacking the orc pawn. The enchanters are mesmerizing the orc centurions, while they are attacking people. Regardless of who the centurions are attacking, you do nothing.<br>
<br>
The centurions are now mesmerized and standing idle. Fred is swinging at the orc pawn. You do nothing.<br>
<br>
Fred shouts: &quot;I am attacking &lt;&gt; Please Assist!&quot; You press your /assist Fred hotkey, and then hit your autoattack button.<br>
<br>
Two things to notice here: First you never click on a monster to get a target - you always use the hotkey to make sure you get the right target. Second, you don't attack until the MA tells you to.<br>
<br>
(The Secondary Assist, or SA, comes into play when the MA dies. He's the backup plan.)<br>
<br>
Once in a while, you'll need to switch targets.<br>
<br>
Fred shouts: &quot;SWITCH TO &lt;&gt; SWITCH NOW!!&quot; You should press your /assist fred hotkey and attack away.<br>
<br>
Loot<br>
Usually people from each group will be assigned to loot should that group get the kill. Let them deal with it. Stay alert for announcements on special drops that you might want to roll on. Always make sure you read and understand the loot rules before you go to a raid - it will save you a lot of hassle, trust me.<br>
<br>
Experience<br>
Raids are about fun and loot more than they are experience. Your group might get some kills, or it might not. Don't be upset if you're not, and don't try to steal the kill by overburning mana or some such. It tends to disrupt the raid by making the monster jump around a lot.<br>
<br>
Wipeouts and resurrections<br>
Sometimes the best laid plans of mice and men and lizards go awry. If the raid gets wiped out, rest assured the leaders will work dilligently on a recovery effort. All you can do is be patient, and know that nobody will be left hanging.<br>
<br>
Going linkdead and dealing with lag<br>
Even the best connections go down sometimes. Just get back in as soon as you can. If you're getting a lot of lag, there are things you can do to help. First off make sure you type:<br>
<br>
/serverfilter on<br>
<br>
This will cut down the amount of data that the server sends to your PC. Also you can turn down the various visual settings, especially particle density, if you are having choppy video. Also to help your visual speed you can try:<br>
<br>
/showspelleffects off<br>
<br>
New info:<br>
With the advent of Shadows of Luclin we have new graphics for characters. These new graphics look great but are a lot more draining on your computer. Even a fairly good machine can be slowed down when there are 20-30 players to draw. Another way to speed up the graphics drawing is to log out, and go to the Options screen, and turn off all the new models. If you get a lot of studder in your image when there are many players on the screen, this could help a lot.<br>
<br>
Time to go home<br>
Sometimes you can't stay til the end of the raid. That's ok. Just let people know that you have to leave - preferably a bit in advance. Generally you can get teleported out of the raid and all is well.<br>
<br>
Notes for specific areas<br>
Just a few tips for specific places<br>
<br>
Hate<br>
You arrive in hate via a wizard porting you up. This place is touchy tho, and agro can be transmitted through the walls. It's very important when you arrive to not touch the walls, and don't sit down to med until you are told it's ok to do so (usually after the nearby mobs are dead). Often you'll be asked to move a little south from the port up spot.<br>
<br>
After fighting for a while, the raid will move to other areas. Stay alert and stay with the group so you don't get lost. If you do get lost, get a location, and die there. Your body will be dragged and you'll be rezzed back to the raid.<br>
<br>
Fear<br>
Fear can be a tricky place. Listen carefully for what you should do after zoning in. Some monsters in fear will teleport you a short way away - if this happens to you, be VERY careful. If something else attacks you, do not go running back to camp with it. Stay in place, get a /loc, and die. Many fear raids have been wiped out by people training the camp.<br>
